Version control

v2

Nov 24, 2019

  • COPDGene binary traits with coding (0 = control, 1 = case, 3 = missing) were marked with class = "bin013" and processed so that 3 was assigned NA.
  • COPDGene quantitative traits were inverse-normally transformed based on moments statistics (skewness and kurtosis) and the Jarque-Bera test results (p-value < 0.5).
    • In result, traits like Emph_Extent_P1 attenuated their het. p-value from 4.9e-03 to 1.42e-04.
  • Checking traits with no covariates revealed such traits as: height, weight (Brians table of covariates) and all blood counts traits (new traits). So we included basic covariates, age and gender, for that traits.
    • In result, Height_CM became the top trait and changed its het. p-value from 2.0e-04 to 8.75e-17. This updated result for height now is in accordance with the clustering results: height has the highest Z-scores and it has the largest trait loading (See Figure 2).
    • Q: no covariats for binary traits FathAsthma and FathEmphysema?
  • The longitudinal traits were normalized as: change between visits 1 and 2 / time passed between visits 1 and 2.
    • The trait names were updated from Change_pctEmph_RLL_Thirona to Change_pctEmph_RLL_Thirona_yr with _yr at the end.

All input and output data were precomputed. So we just need to load these data.

dir_data <- "../data"

file_phewas <- file.path(dir_data, "phewas.rdata")

SNP weights (H)

Ht <- getHt(clust)
Ht_norm <- t(apply(Ht, 1, function(x) x / sum(x)))
get_top_snps <- function(w, thr) names(w[w > thr]) 

thr_top_snps <- 0.5
snps_clust1 <- get_top_snps(Ht_norm[, 1], thr_top_snps)
snps_clust2 <- get_top_snps(Ht_norm[, 2], thr_top_snps)
snps_clust3 <- get_top_snps(Ht_norm[, 3], thr_top_snps)

Top cluster 1 SNPs: 28 / (28 + 17) asthma SNPs
